04667nam a22006375i 9780226731742DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020038658  a97802267317427 a10.7208/97802267317422doi  a(DE-B1597)589010  a(OCoLC)1243547962  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aQ143.R26bD337 2021 4aQ143.R26 7aBIO0000002bisacsh04a509.21 aDiMeo, Michelle, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLady Ranelagh :bThe Incomparable Life of Robert Boyle's Sister /cMichelle DiMeo. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b10 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSynthesis00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tNote on Conventions -- tIntroduction -- t1. Birth, Childhood, and Marriage (1615– 42) -- t2. Early Days in the Hartlib Circle (1642– 48) -- t3. Formative Years in Natural Philosophy and Medicine (1649– 56) -- t4. Return to Ireland (1656– 59) -- t5. Death of the Hartlib Circle and Birth of the Royal Society (1658– 67) -- t6. Plague, Providence, and Medical Practice (1665– 67) -- t7. Robert Boyle Moves In (1668– 90) -- tConclusion: Death and Legacy -- tAcknowledgments -- tAppendix: Boyle Family Genealogy -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor centuries, historians have speculated about the life of Katherine Jones, Lady Ranelagh. Dominant depictions show her either as a maternal figure to her younger brother Robert Boyle, one of the most significant scientists of his day, or as a patroness of the European correspondence network now known as the Hartlib circle—but neither portrait captures the depth of her intellect or the range of her knowledge and influence. Philosophers, mathematicians, politicians, and religious authorities sought her opinion on everything from decimalizing the currency to producing Hebrew grammars. She practiced medicine alongside distinguished male physicians, treating some of the most elite patients in London. Her medical recipes, political commentaries, and testimony concerning the philosophers’ stone gained international circulation. She was an important influence on Boyle and a formidable thinker in her own right. Drawing from a wealth of new archival sources, Michelle DiMeo fills out Lady Ranelagh’s legacy in the context of a historically sensitive and nuanced interpretation of gender, science, and religion. The book re-creates the intellectual life of one of the most respected and influential women in seventeenth-century Europe, revealing how she managed to gain the admiration of diverse contemporaries, effect social change, and shape contemporary science.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aBoyle, Robert,-1627-1691-Family. 0aMedicinezGreat BritainxHistoryy17th century. 0aRanelagh, Lady. 0aSciencezGreat BritainxHistoryy17th century. 0aWomen intellectualszGreat BritainvBiography. 0aWomen intellectuals-Great Britain-Biography. 0aWomen physicianszGreat BritainvBiography. 0aWomen physicians-Great Britain-Biography. 0aWomen scientistszGreat BritainvBiography. 0aWomen scientists-Great Britain-Biography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh  aLady Ranelagh, Robert Boyle, Hartlib Circle, alchemy, medical recipes, early modern science, gender, religion, medicine, biography.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073919040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226731742423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226731742/original  a978-3-11-073919-0  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021b